**1st Paper brief**
Research question
The main question was essentially: how should AI systems be designed
so they meet real users’ explanation needs in practice?
More specifically, the authors wanted to understand the gap between
existing algorithmic XAI methods and the actual needs of people designing
AI products for users. They explored this by interviewing 20 UX and design
practitioners working on AI products.



What they did:
They conducted interviews with those practitioners and used an “algorithm-informed 
XAI question bank” as a probe. This question bank represents explanation needs
as the kinds of questions users may ask an AI system, such as wanting to know
why the system made a decision, what data it used, how confident it is, or what
could change the outcome.

 (P.S. The XAI question bank is basically a structured list of common questions
that users may want to ask an AI system when they want to understand its behavior.
In that paper, the authors describe it as an algorithm-informed tool where
explainability needs are represented as prototypical user questions about the AI.)

Main findings
The paper found that there is a real mismatch between current XAI research and 
real-world product design needs. Existing XAI work often focuses on technical
explanation methods, but practitioners need explanations that are tied to user
goals, context, and product experience.
Another key finding is that users’ needs can be better understood as questions
they want to ask the AI, rather than as one fixed explanation format. That is why
the authors proposed the XAI question bank as a practical tool for designing more
 user-centered explainability.


**2nd Paper Brief**

Research question
The paper asks, in essence, what should “Interactive Human Centered AI” mean, 
and what properties should such systems have so that AI supports people rather
 than just being technically powerful.

Main idea
It is mostly a conceptual paper, not an experiment paper. The author
 proposes a definition of Interactive Human Centered AI as AI that allows
  real-time interaction, exploration, and manipulation, is built for human
   benefit, and is transparent about who controls the data and algorithms.

Main findings / arguments
The paper argues that human-centered AI should let people:
interact with AI in real time
see the effect of changes immediately
understand why and how decisions are made
know what data is being used
know who has control
understand both the benefits and the risks of the AI system.




**A PROBLEM THAT MAY ACCURE IN A WORKSPACE
SCENARIO THAT MAY BE CURED WITH AI**

people often bornout during huge a overload at work or a lot of pressure, this leads to
a huge loss of motivation, productivity, wellbeing and team morale.

An AI system could help by analyzing the problem and help with annoying and small tasks, such as:
- automatic documentation
- automatic tasks management 
- controll stress levels

1. Bakker, Demerouti, & Sanz-Vergel (2014)

Burnout and Work Engagement: The JD–R Approach

This paper explains that burnout often happens when employees face high job demands, 
such as too much work, pressure, and emotional strain, while not having enough support
or resources. The authors use the Job Demands–Resources model to show that these
conditions can lead to exhaustion and disengagement, while enough resources can
improve motivation and engagement. This paper strongly supports your idea that
overload at work can damage wellbeing, motivation, and performance.

2. Belloni, Villosio, & Moro (2022)

The Impact of Working Conditions on Mental Health

This paper studies how working conditions affect mental health and shows that poor
or stressful work environments can have a real negative effect on employees’ psychological
wellbeing. It is useful for your topic because it supports the argument that workplace
pressure and unhealthy conditions are not just uncomfortable, but can seriously harm
mental health.

3. Soto, Karapanos, Gonçalves, & Campos (2021)

Observing and Predicting Knowledge Worker Stress, Focus and Awakeness in the Wild

This paper looks at knowledge workers in real-life conditions and studies stress,
 focus, and alertness during work. It shows that stress in office-style work can
  be observed and predicted using data collected during everyday work activities. 
  This supports your idea that AI can help detect stress early instead of waiting 
  until burnout becomes severe.

4. Vanttola et al. (2024)

Different Methods to Detect Stress in Knowledge Workers: A Pilot Study for Long-term Monitoring

This study explores different ways to detect stress in knowledge workers over
 a longer period. The researchers found that simple self-reports and computer-use
  data may help identify stress with relatively low effort from employees.
   This supports the “control stress levels” part of your idea because it shows
    that stress monitoring can be practical and not necessarily overly intrusive.

5. Asthana, Hilleli, He, & Halfaker (2025)

Summaries, Highlights, and Action Items: Design, Implementation 
and Evaluation of an LLM-powered Meeting Recap System

This paper presents an AI system that automatically creates meeting recaps, highlights,
 and action items. The study shows that such systems can help reduce manual follow-up
  work and make meetings easier to review and organize, although they still have limitations
   like missing important details or relevance for specific users. For your idea, this
    paper supports the claim that AI can reduce overload by helping with documentation
    and small coordination tasks.


These papers together show that heavy workload and pressure can lead to burnout and lower wellbeing,
 while AI can help by detecting stress and reducing repetitive administrative work, such as
  documentation and meeting follow-up.